a+Constitution&desc=CAROLINA+YOUTH+SHOT+BY+TEACHER&pqatl=google Carolina youth shot by teacher], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (February 25, 1903)</ref><ref>[https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/ajc_historic/access/560490212.html?dids=560490212:560490212&FMT=CITE&FMTS=CITE:AI&date=Sep+20%2C+1903&author=&pub=The+Atlanta+Constitution&desc=REUBEN+PITTS+GETS+FREEDOM&pqatl=google Reuben Pitts gets freedom], ''[[The Atlanta Constitution]]'' (September 20, 1903)</ref>\n|-\n|July 21, 1903\n|[[Jackson, Kentucky]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At Cave Run School, James Barrett and Mack Howard fought a duel with pistols over a card game, killing each other. Another student James Vires, aged 12, suffered a wound while sitting at his desk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=LAH19030722.2.14&srpos=1&e=20-07-1903-22-07-1903--en--20-LAH-1--txt-IN-barrett----|work=Los Angeles Herald, Volume XXX, Number 288|title=Deulists Fatally Shot|date=22 July 1903}}</ref>\n|-\n|April 6, 1904\n|[[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], United States\n| Henry Schaze\n|1 dead\n|\n|Two students had been fighting over a girl for the better part of a year. Finally, Henry Schaze pushed 16-year-old Paul Jelick to the ground and shot him dead.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 95, Number 129, 7 April 1904</ref>\n|-\n|November 16, 1904\n|[[Riverside, California]], United States\n|\n| 2 dead\n| 1 injured\n|At Indian School, a gun fight broke out between pupils. Charles Colby was shot in the head, then returned fire, killing Tom Bucanoros and fatally wounding Fred Smith.<ref>''San Francisco Call,'' Volume 96, Number 170, 17 November 1904</ref>\n|-\n|December 16, 1904\n|[[Magee, Mississippi]], United States\n| E. E. Mangum\n|1 dead\n|1 injured\n|E. E. Mangum was shot through the head and killed by the principal of the high school, Professor J. E. Woodward, after the student argued about punishment of his son and the argument became violent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cdnc.ucr.edu/cdnc/cgi-bin/cdnc?a=d&cl=search&d=SFC19041217.2.76.22&srpos=1&e=15-12-1904-17-12-1904--en--20-SFC-1--txt-IN-mangum----|work=San Francisco Call, Volume 97, Number 17|title=High School Principal Shoots Irate Parent|date=17 December 1904}}</ref>\n|-\n|February 9, 1905\n|[[Colusa, California]], United States\n|William Ingrim\n| \n|2 injured\n|At the request of his childhood friend, Pearl Cruse, Elmer Hildreth - a 17-year-old non-student, attended a meeting between Miss Cruse and her teacher. This meeting ended ended in \"a hand to hand\" encounter between the teacher and Cruse. Hildreth became involved in a physical confrontation with school trustee Ingrim, whom he shot. He was found to have acted in self-defense. Ingrim survived the shooting.<ref>''Colusa Sun Herald'' 15 February 1905</ref>\n|-\n| September 12, 1905\n| [[Athens, Tennessee]], United States\n| Ernest Powers, 15\n| 1 dead\n| \n| 15-year-old student Ernest Powers fatally stabbed his teacher Elbert Wattanbarger, when he attempted to whip him for throwing stones.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1905/09/17/archives/surrender-boy-who-slew-teacher.html Surrender Boy Who Slew Teacher], ''The New York Times'' (September 17, 1905)</ref>\n|-\n\n| April 15, 1908\n| [[Asheville, North Carolina]], United States\n| Dr. Curtis O. Swinney\n| 2 dead\n| \n| Dr. Curtis O. Swinney shot and fatally wounded his 16-year-old daughter Nellie in a reception room at Normal and Collegiate Institute. He was reported to be mad at her for a harmless April Fools prank she had played at school. He then committed suicide by shooting himself in the head.<ref>[https://tidingsofyore.wordpress.com/2013/04/01/father-kills-teenage-daughter-then-suicides-after-april-fools-day-prank/| Father Kills Teenage Daughter, Then Suicides After April Fools\u2019 Day Prank], ''The Manning Times'' (April 22, 1908)</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===1910s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 10, 1910\n| [[Ione, California]], United States\n| Albert Brown<br>Eugene Griffin\n|\n|\n| At the reform school, [[Preston School of Industry]], students Albert Brown and Eugene Griffin tried to escape after stealing a revolver from the school. They shot at Captain William H. White who pursued them. No one was hurt, but the two boys were transferred to the state penitentiary.<ref>''Amador Ledger,'' 11 March 1910</ref>\n|-\n| September 23, 1912\n| [[Sankt P\u00f6lten]], [[Austria]]\n| Rudolf Hlawat\n| 1 dead\n| \n| Rudolf Hlawat, a student at a [[Gymnasium (school)|gymnasium]] in St. P\u00f6lten, shot at his teacher, Prof. Schmidt, with a revolver. He also shot at the school janitor before shooting himself twice in the head. Hlawat died in hospital, the only casualty.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19120924&seite=2&zoom=2 Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf den Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (September 24, 1912)</ref>\n|-\n| October 9, 1913\n| [[Szeged]], [[Hungary]]\n| Johann Skultety, 14\n| 1 dead\n| \n| After he had been reprimanded by his teacher, Prof. Horvarth, for missing classes, Johann Skultety, a gymnasium student in Szeged, barged into his classroom and fired with a revolver at the teacher, missing him. He committed suicide by shooting himself in the heart.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19131010&seite=3&zoom=2 Ein Revolverattentat eines Gymnasiasten auf seinen Professor], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (October 10, 1913)</ref>\n|-\n| April 12, 1919\n| [[Ogden City, Utah]], United States\n| \n| \n|1 injured\n|During a high school assembly, six boys shot off their guns, with permission, thinking they were loaded with blanks. Teacher Miss