 students\n| 5+ dead\n| ~10 injured\n| [[Wilno school massacre]]. A massacre occurred at [[Joachim Lelewel]] High School in [[Wilno]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]]. At about 11 a.m., during the final exams, at least two eighth-grade students attacked the board of examiners with revolvers and hand grenades, killing at least one teacher, several students and themselves. An investigation revealed that the students had established a Communist youth organisation to counter the principal's strict management of the school. The members of this organisation had met the day before the exams in a tavern, to discuss the actions. <ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nfp&datum=19250507&seite=1&zoom=2 Revolversch\u00fcsse und Bombenw\u00fcrfe gegen Lehrer], ''[[Neue Freie Presse]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0A16FF3B5B12738DDDAE0894DD405B858EF1D3 Bomb Kills Three Boy Raiders Who Shoot Up Vilna School], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 7, 1925)</ref>\n|-\n| May 18, 1927\n| [[Bath, Michigan]], United States\n| [[Andrew Kehoe]], 55\n| 45\n| 58\n| [[Bath School disaster]]. School board member [[Andrew Kehoe]] set up a series of explosions in the [[Bath Consolidated School]].  Before blowing up the school, Kehoe murdered his wife and set fire to his farmhouse.  After the bombings, Kehoe detonated his shrapnel-filled vehicle outside the school, committing suicide and wounding others. The bombings constitutes the deadliest act of mass murder in any type of school setting in U.S. history.\n|}\n\n===1930s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 5, 1931\n| [[Pristina]], [[Yugoslavia]]\n|\n|\n| 1 injured\n| A student named Ismailovic shot and stabbed his teacher several times at a gymnasium in Pristina after he had been expelled due to low grades. Ismailovic was later arrested at a cemetery when he tried to hang himself.<ref>[http://anno.onb.ac.at/cgi-content/anno?apm=0&aid=nzg&datum=19310306&seite=5&zoom=2 Die Rache eines durchgefallenen Gymnasiasten], ''[[Die Neue Zeitung]]'' (March 6, 1931)</ref>\n|-\n| September 14, 1934\n| [[Gill, Massachusetts]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Headmaster Elliott Speer was murdered by a shotgun blast through the window of his study at [[Northfield Mount Hermon School]]. The crime was never solved.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,848774,00.html |title=Education: Berkshire Mystery |publisher=Time.com |date=1937-06-07 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 24, 1937\n| [[Toledo, Ohio]], United States\n| Robert Snyder, 12\n|\n| 2 injured\n| 12-year-old Robert Snyder shot and wounded his principal, June Mapes, in her office at Arlington public school when she declined his request to call a classmate. He later shot and wounded himself but survived.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SO4KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=z08DAAAAIBAJ&pg=4212,6557992&dq= Lay shooting to gang tales], ''Prescott Evening Courier'' (September 24, 1937)</ref>\n|-\n| June 24, 1939\n| Tirpan, Bulgaria\n| ..., 15\n| 4 dead\n| \n| A 15-year-old student killed three teachers with a revolver at a school in Tirpan, southern Bulgaria after being expelled. The boy, who had already been expelled from three other schools during the year for bad behaviour, afterwards committed suicide.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19390625&id=xec-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=KU0MAAAAIBAJ&pg=5076,7768567 Boy kills teachers], ''[[The Tuscaloosa News]]'' (June 25, 1939)</ref><ref>[http://www.wbc.poznan.pl/dlibra/plain-content?id=118487 Ucze\u0144 zastrzeli\u0142 nauczycielk\u0119 i pope\u0142ni\u0142 samob\u00f3jstwo], ''[[Or\u0119downik Wrzesi\u0144ski]]'' (July 4, 1939)</ref>\n|}\n\n===1940s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| May 6, 1940\n| [[South Pasadena, California]], United States\n| Verlin Spencer, 38\n| 5 dead\n| 2 injured\n| After being removed as principal of South Pasadena Junior High School, Verlin Spencer shot six school officials, killing five, before attempting to commit suicide by shooting himself in the stomach. He was sentenced to five consecutive life sentences, and was released early on parole in 1970.<ref>[http://fultonhistory.com/Process%20small/Newspapers/Oswego%20Palladium/Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20pdf/Newspaper%20%20Oswego%20Palladium%20May-June%201940%20-%200085.pdf 4 dead, 3 dying from gunfire of ousted educator, ''Oswego Palladium-Times''] (May 7, 1940)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1940/05/10/archives/5-dead-in-school-killings-teacher-at-pasadena-succumbs-slayer-in.html 5 dead in school killings], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (May 10, 1940)</ref>\n|-\n| May 23, 1940\n|[[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Matthew Gillespie, 62\n|\n| 1 injured\n| Infuriated by a personal grievance, Matthew Gillespie, 62-year-old janitor at the junior school of the Dwight School for Girls, shot and critically wounded Mrs. Marshall Coxe, secretary of the junior school.\n|-\n| July 4, 1940\n|[[Valhalla, New York]], United States\n| Joseph Moshell, 47\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Angered by the refusal of his daughter, 15-years-old Melba Moshell, to leave a boarding school in Valhalla and return to his home in Philadelphia, Joseph Moshell, 47, visited the school and shot and killed the girl. The girl had previously expressed fear of her father.  He then shot himself, but survived his injuries.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1940/07/05/archives/father-slays-girl-in-boarding-school-episcopal-nun-in-westchester.html| FATHER SLAYS GIRL IN BOARDING SCHOOL; Episcopal Nun in Westchester Sees Man Shoot Daughter, Who Feared Him, and Himself] |''[[The New York Times]]'' (July 5, 1940)</ref>\n|-\n| October 2, 1942\n| [[New York City, New York]], United States\n| Joseph Annunziata, 19 <br> Neil Simonelli, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Joseph Annunziata and Neil Simonelli shot and killed teacher Irwin Goodman at William J. Gaynor Junior High School, after he had caught them smoking in a washroom. Neither Annunziata nor Simonelli was a student at the school.<ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0F15F83458167B93C1A9178BD95F468485F9 Two Boys Kill Teacher in School After 'Showing Off' by Smoking], ''The New York Times'' (October 3, 1942)</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=nr4KAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w00DAAAAIBAJ&pg=5146,4095599&dq= Murder in a zoot suit], ''[[The Deseret News]]'' (October 10, 1942)</ref>\n|-\n| May 28, 1943\n| [[Brownsville, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Thomas Celestine, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 16-year-old Ettra Cimagha was stabbed to death by 16-year-old Thomas Celestine during a fight at Brownsville Junior High School.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=8jcxAAAAIBAJ&sjid=AWoDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2169,3353986&dq=school+stabbing+death&hl=en |title=Schoolboy Is Stabbed To Death In Scuffle |publisher=News.google.ca |date=1943-05-29 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n|June 26, 1946\n|[[New York City, New York]], United States\n|\n| \n|1 injured\n|A 15-year-old student who balked at turning over his pocket money to a gang of seven youths was shot in the chest at Public School 147 annex of the Brooklyn High School for Automotive Trades.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/06/26/archives/boy-in-school-shot-robbed-by-7-thugs-gang-of-youths-also-attempts.html|work=The New 