8}}</ref>\n|-\n| May 1, 1958\n| [[Massapequa, New York]], United States\n| Bruce Zator, 15\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 15-year-old freshman Timothy Wall is shot to death by classmate Bruce Zator in a washroom of [[Massapequa High School]].<ref>{{cite news|author=Roy R. Silver (Special to The New York Times). |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0F10FE3C59107B93C3A9178ED85F4C8585F9 |title=Massapequa boy slain in school; Ambushed in Washroom \u2013 Classmate, 15, Confesses and Re-enacts Crime |publisher=Select.nytimes.com |date=1958-05-01 |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 16, 1959\n| [[Edmonton, Alberta]], Canada\n| Stan Williamson, 19\n| 1 dead\n| 5 injured\n| 19-year-old Stan Williamson opened fire with a rifle inside [[Ross Sheppard High School]], killing 16-year-old Howard Gates and wounding five teenage girls. Three 18-year-old students tackled the gunman and held him down until he could be arrested by police.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=fL9UAAAAIBAJ&sjid=-jsNAAAAIBAJ&pg=4550,2676035&dq=school+shooting&hl=en |title=High school gun spree kills one, wounds five |publisher=News.google.ca |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 21, 1959\n| [[New York, New York]], United States\n| Unknown gunman\n| 1 dead\n| \n| A teenage boy was shot and killed at Morris High School. This was suspected to be related to gang activity. On September 23-24, police arrested twenty-seven men and boys and confiscated all of their weapons. Police suspected these men were disparate members  of multiple gangs, that were gathering weapons in anticipation of the start of a gang war over the murder. The prospective gang war was headed off by this seizure before it began. <ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.nytimes.com/1959/09/24/archives/27-seized-in-bronx-with-gang-arsenal-27-seized-with-gang-arsenal-as.html |title= 27 Seized in Bronx With Gang Arsenal; 27 Seized With Gang Arsenal As Fight in Bronx Is Blocked |work=New York Times|date= September 24, 1959}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1960s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| March 30, 1960\n| [[Alice, Texas]], United States\n| Donna Dvorak, 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Donna Dvorak, 14, brought a target pistol to Dubose Junior High School, and fatally shot Bobby Whitford, 15, in their 9th grade science class.  Dvorak believed Whitford posed a threat to one of her girlfriends.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jthHAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IoAMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3467,122520&dq=dvorak&hl=en|work=The Victoria Advocate|title=Youth Fatally Shot In Crowded Class|date=Mar 31, 1960}}</ref>\n|-\n| March 4, 1961\n| [[Kung\u00e4lv]], [[Sweden]] \n| Ove Conry Andersson, 17\n| 1 dead\n| 6 injured\n| |[[Kung\u00e4lv school shooting]]. A 17-year-old student fired fifteen bullets into a crowd at a school dance at Kung\u00e4lvs L\u00e4roverk (a/k/a Thorildskolan), killing one student and wounding six others before escaping. He turned himself in to local police the following morning and was arrested.\n|-\n| October 17, 1961\n| [[Denver, Colorado]], United States\n| Tennyson Beard, 14\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Tennyson Beard, 14, got into an argument with William Hachmeister, 15, at Morey Junior High School. During the argument Beard pulled out a revolver and shot at Hachmeister, wounding him. Deborah Faith Humphrey, 14, was fatally wounded by another shot. Beard was arrested after fleeing the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=PAozAAAAIBAJ&sjid=w-cDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4617,710365 |title=School Fight Mushrooms Into Murder |publisher=News.google.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 26, 1962\n| [[Taipei]], [[Taiwan]]\n| Tsui Yin, 41\n| 7 dead\n| 3 injured\n| Tsui Yin, a 41-year-old former physical education teacher at Li Shing junior high school in Taipei, shot and killed the principal, the principal's wife and five other faculty members with a pistol, in revenge for his dismissal. He wounded three others, among them the principal's daughter, before escaping in a taxi. He was arrested and sentenced to death.<ref>Admits killing 7 for revenge, ''[[Pacific Stars and Stripes]]'' (January 27, 1962)</ref><ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=H2gUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=KQEEAAAAIBAJ&pg=7282,775520&dq= Teacher who slew 7 denied wish to see pupil perform], ''[[Toledo Blade]]'' (July 26, 1962)</ref>\n|-\n|May 7, 1963\n|[[Paterson, New Jersey]]\n|Ralph Best, 43\n|\n|6 injured\n|Gun engraver Ralph Best opened fire from his second floor room with a .22 caliber hunting rifle on 50 children playing in the schoolyard at Paterson School 14 on the evening of May 7, 1963. An alcoholic and epileptic, he fired after the children ignored his demands they leave the playground. Charged with \"atrocious assault\", Best pled insanity. His first trial ended in a mistrial, and he was never re-tried.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northjersey.com|title=An oft-forgotten school shooting|last=Maag|first=Christopher|date=January 21, 2019|work=The Record|access-date=|page=1A}}</ref>\n|-\n| April 27, 1966\n| [[Bay Shore, New York]], United States\n| James Arthur Frampton, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Teacher John S. Lane, 48, was shot and fatally wounded when he tried to stop 16-year-old student James Arthur Frampton, who was walking with a shotgun in the high school, seeking students with whom he had argued. Lane died of his wounds on June 13, 1966.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/28/archives/li-teacher-shot-by-boy-in-school-badly-wounded-trying-to-halt.html L.I. teacher shot by boy in school], ''The New York Times'' (April 28, 1966)</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1966/04/29/archives/li-boy-held-in-shooting-faces-psychiatric-exam.html L.I. Boy Held in Shooting Faces Psychiatric Exam], ''The New York Times'' (April 29, 1966)</ref><ref>[https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0B1FFD3559137B93C6A8178DD85F428685F9 Teacher Shot by Youth Dies in Bay Shore Hospital], ''[[The New York Times]]'' (June 14, 1966)</ref>\n|-\n| October 5, 1966\n| [[Grand Rapids, Minnesota]], United States\n| David M. Black Jr., 15\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| David Black, a 15-year-old student at [[Grand Rapids High School]], took a pistol to school, shooting student Kevin Roth and administrator Forrest L. Willey, with whom he had argued. Willey died of his wound eight days later.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbine-angels.com/grand_rapids_high.htm |title=A wound still fresh//The survivor of a 1966 school shooting in Minnesota is still coming to grips with the pain \u2013 and with his own role in the tragedy |publisher=Columbine-angels.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| September 26, 1967\n| [[Dayton, Ohio]], United States\n| Will Edward Dixon, 19\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Thomas Prinz, a 21-year-old football coach at Wilbur Wright High School, was stabbed to death by 19-year-old Will Edward Dixon. The stabbing occurred when Prinz attempted to escort Dixon off the playing field. Dixon was a former student and drop-out from the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=iJYuAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IUgDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5062,4240840&dq=school+stabbing+death&hl=en |title=Dayton Coach Stabbed To Death By Youth |publisher=News.google.ca |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 1, 1967\n| [[Dundee]], [[Scotland]], United Kingdom\n| [[Robert Mone]], 19\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 19-year-old soldier Robert Mone entered [[St John's RC High School]] armed with a shotgun and took a class hostage. He sexually abused the children. The teacher, Nanette Hanson, convinced Mone, who had already raped one girl, to let the children go. Mone fatally shot her in the head. Mone had been expelled three years before and was apparently seeking revenge; he was found to be insane and sent to the [[State Hospital]] in [[Carstairs]].<ref>[http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/news/scottish-news/2007/11/02/tribute-to-teacher-killed-by-monster-mone-86908-20049591/ Tribute To Teacher Killed By Monster Mone], ''[[Daily Record (Scotland)|Daily Record]]'' (November 2, 2007)</ref>\n|-\n| January 30, 1968\n| [[Miami]], [[Florida]], United States\n| Blanche Patricia Ward, 16\n| 1 dead\n|\n| 16-year-old Blanche Ward shot and killed fellow student Linda Lipscomb, 16, with a pistol at Miami Jackson High School. According to Ward, she was threatened with a razor by Lipscomb during an argument and in the ensuing struggle her gun went off.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=vBoMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=vlwDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4031,176485&dq= Fatal shooting brings action], ''[[St. Petersburg Times]]'' (February 1, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| March 25, 1968\n| [[High Point, North Carolina]],  United States\n| Gerald Locklear, 16\n| 1 dead\n| \n| David Walker, 15, was shot to death just outside Central High School by Gerald Locklear, 15.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19680326&id=j7VWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=gOkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5447,3659292&hl=en Student Held In Slaying], ''[[The Spokesman-Review]]'' (March 26, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| May 22, 1968\n| [[Miami]], [[Florida]], United States\n| Ernest Lee Grissom, 15\n|\n| 2 injured\n| Ernest Lee Grissom, a 15-year-old student at Drew Junior High School, shot and seriously wounded a teacher and a 13-year-old student after he had been reprimanded for a disturbance.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=i-MTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=SQUEAAAAIBAJ&pg=2587,3245401&dq= Teacher, student serious following shooting by youth], ''[[Ocala Star-Banner]]'' (May 23, 1968)</ref>\n|-\n| January 23, 1969\n| [[Washington, District of Columbia]], United States\n| Ronald Joyner, 18\n| 1 dead\n|\n| [[Cardozo Senior High School]] assistant principal Herman Clifford, 45, was shot to death in the hallway by Ronald Joyner, 18, while scuffling with three youths who robbed the school's bank.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1969/01/25/archives/principals-aide-in-capital-is-killed-chasing-thieves.html?sq=%2522Clifford%2522&scp=16&st=p|work=The New York Times|title=Principal's Aide in Capital is Killed Chasing Thieves|date=Jan 25, 1969}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 19, 1969\n| [[Tomah, Wisconsin]], United States\n| ..., 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Principal Martin Mogensen is shot to death in his office by a 14-year-old boy armed with a [[shotgun]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.madison.com/wsj/spe/Weston/index.php?ntid=101225 |title=Some other incidents involving guns at Wisconsin schools |publisher=Madison.com |date=2011-02-15 |accessdate=2011-03-12 }}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1314&dat=19691120&id=JUIVAAAAIBAJ&sjid=HAgEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5900,1913651 |title=Shots Kill High School Principal |publisher=News.google.com |accessdate=2011-03-12}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===1970s===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:65px;\"| Date\n! style=\"width:85px;\"| Location\n! style=\"width:75px;\"| Attacker(s)\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Dead{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! data-sort-type=\"number\" style=\"width:75px;\"| Injured{{r|group=lower-alpha|note_a}}\n! Description\n|-\n| January 5, 1970\n| [[Washington, District of Columbia]], United States\n| Unnamed student\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Tyrone Perry, 15, was shot to death and a 14-year-old boy was wounded at Hine Junior High School.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=AfRYAAAAIBAJ&sjid=cOsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=3025,1894998&dq=boy+shot+at+school&hl=en|work=The Spokesman-Review|title=Boys Hurt, Killed In Shootings|date=January 6, 1970}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 1, 1971\n| [[Philadelphia, Pennsylvania]], United States\n| Kevin Simmons, 14\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Samson L. Freedman, a 56-year-old art teacher, was shot to death by Kevin Simmons at Leeds Junior High School, after having the student suspended for cursing.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/02/archives/art-teacher-slain-philadelphia-police-arrest-youth-14.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160923170859/http://www.nytimes.com/1971/02/02/archives/art-teacher-slain-philadelphia-police-arrest-youth-14.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=23 September 2016|title=Art Teacher Slain; Philadelphia Police Arrest Youth, 14 \u2013 The New York Times|date=23 September 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n| November 3, 1971\n| [[Carlsbad, New Mexico]],\nUnited States\n| Michael O'Hearn, 22\n| 1 dead\n| 1 injured\n| Michael O'Hearn barricaded himself in a storage tower of Carlsbad Mid-High School, in [[Carlsbad, New Mexico]], for about two hours with two firearms. He fired about two dozen rounds at police officers, injuring one, before committing suicide.<ref name=\"stpetersburg110471\">{{cite news|title=Sniper's Victim: Himself|date=1971-11-04|url =https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=k9IMAAAAIBAJ&sjid=tWADAAAAIBAJ&pg=3115,1900854&|work=[[St. Petersburg Times]]|accessdate = 2009-04-18}}</ref>\n|-\n| January 24, 1972\n| [[Stow, Ohio]], United States\n| \n|\n| 1 injured\n| A 16-year-old student at Stow High School shot and wounded his chemistry teacher during an argument.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=dk8LAAAAIBAJ&sjid=a1IDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5155,1313401&dq= Youth shoots chem teacher], ''[[The Bryan Times]]'' (January 25, 1972)</ref>\n|-\n| January 7\u201312, 1973\n| [[Balassagyarmat]], Hungary\n| Andr\u00e1s Pintye, 18 and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Pintye, 17\n| 1 dead\n| Several hostages required medical attention\n| Brothers Andr\u00e1s and L\u00e1szl\u00f3 Pintye, sons of local Communist Party officials, have acquired a [[FEG PA-63|PA-63]] pistol and an [[AMD-65|AMD]] assault rifle and assaulted a local girls' dormitory. They held an unknown number of teenage girls hostage for several days, demanding free passage to Budapest's international airport and a flight to Austria. Finally, when they planned to murder some of the hostages, a police sniper shot Andr\u00e1s dead through the window, then the police stormed the building, arresting L\u00e1szl\u00f3. He was sentenced to 15 years of prison, from which he was released in 1984, serving a little more than 11 years. Four other persons were sentenced for aiding the perpetrators. The case deeply traumatized Hungary which has never seen such events before. A feature film titled T\u00faszt\u00f6rt\u00e9net (Hostage Story) was made about the events in 1989.<ref>[[:hu:Balassagyarmati t\u00faszdr\u00e1ma#A t.C3\u00baszdr\u00e1ma ut\u00f3\u00e9lete|Wikipedia (Hungarian) article about the hostage drama]]</ref>{{Circular reference|date=May 2017}}\n|-\n| February 26, 1973\n| [[Richmond, Virginia]], United States\n|\n| 1 dead\n|\n| Wayne Phillips, 17, was shot to death when he was caught between two youths who were fighting in the hallway of [[Armstrong High School (Richmond, Virginia)|Armstrong High School]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=CTJgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s28NAAAAIBAJ&pg=4009,6506820&dq=boy+killed+at+school&hl=en |newspaper=The Phoenix|title=Boy Killed In Gun Battle|date=February 27, 1973}}</ref>\n|-\n| July 1973\n|\n|\n|\n|\n| In the [[attack on St Alberts School]], [[Zimbabwe African National Liberation Army]] (ZANLA) cadres captured 292 pupils and staff from the school and [[death march|force-marched]] them north towards [[Mozambique (Portugal)|Mozambique]], where the ZANLA bases were. The march was intercepted by the [[Rhodesian Security Forces]] before the cadres crossed the border, and all but eight of the children and staff were recovered.<ref>{{cite book|title=Counter-Insurgency in Rhodesia|last=Cilliers|first=Jackie|location=London, Sydney & Dover, New Hampshire|publisher=Croom Helm|date=December 1984|isbn=978-0-7099-3412-7|page=18}}</ref>\n|-\n| February 2, 1974\n| [[San Luca]], Italy\